Plaza Sésamo: ¡Haz que tu familia cuente en el Censo del 2020!

Nos asociamos con Sesame Street para ayudar a correr la voz sobre la importancia del Censo 2020 y el recuento de niños pequeños. El Censo del 2020 ayuda a determinar qué áreas cumplen los requisitos para recibir recursos importantes de los que dependerán los niños y las familias durante los próximos 10 años:

Aproximadamente el 5 por ciento de los niños menores de cinco años no fueron contados en el Censo del 2010. Eso equivale a 1 millón de bebes y niños, el mayor conteo incompleto de todos los grupos de edad. Necesitamos su ayuda para cerrar esta brecha en el Censo del 2020.

Responder al censo es más fácil que nunca. Usted puede completar el cuestionario del censo por internet, por teléfono o por correo. Para empezar a darle forma al futuro de los niños, visite https://go.usa.gov/xdV8M.

https://youtu.be/hq3NrRToG0k

post_text:
Sesame Street: Make Your Family Count in the 2020 Census!

We partnered with Sesame Street to help spread the word about the importance of the 2020 Census and the count of young children. Results determine which areas qualify for the critical resources that children and families depend on for the next 10 years—basically an entire childhood!

An estimated 5 percent of kids under the age of five were missed in the 2010 Census. At about 1 million babies and young children, that’s the largest undercount of any age group. We need your help closing this gap in the 2020 Census.

Responding to the census is easier than ever. You can complete the census questionnaire online, by phone or by mail. Start shaping their future by going to https://go.usa.gov/xdKXZ.

https://youtu.be/KZmLI7eYjmw

DILLON MIDDLE SCHOOL:

This school year Dillon Middle School participated in the statewide South Carolina Junior Book Award program in two ways:

* A number of students read at least three of the books that were nominated for the Junior Book Award, and these students cast their votes for the book they thought should win. The winning book (statewide) was 𝘙𝘦𝘴𝘵𝘢𝘳𝘵 by Gordon Korman.

* Mrs. Driggers's 8th-grade Art class designed a banner which was entered into the statewide Junior Book Award banner contest. The banner represented the book 𝘔𝘪𝘭𝘦𝘴 𝘔𝘰𝘳𝘢𝘭𝘦𝘴: 𝘚𝘱𝘪𝘥𝘦𝘳 𝘔𝘢𝘯 which was one of the nominated books. The DMS banner won 3rd place in the contest! The 3rd place win came with a $50 prize which will be donated to the Art department for future banners.

DILLON HIGH SCHOOL:

Varnecia Gause, a former student of Dillon High School, addressed the female class of 2020 on March 13, 2020. She is an employee of Pepsi-Cola of Atlanta, Georgia. Varnecia and her sister, Varnetta, a nurse in Columbia, S.C., are dedicated to giving back to their community through motivating and mentoring female students. Also, they are offering scholarships to deserving female high school graduating seniors intending to pursue a course of study at a four-year institution. We are proud of these young ladies.

LAKE VIEW HIGH SCHOOL:

After reading 𝘉𝘭𝘰𝘰𝘥, 𝘉𝘶𝘭𝘭𝘦𝘵𝘴, 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘉𝘰𝘯𝘦𝘴: 𝘛𝘩𝘦 𝘚𝘵𝘰𝘳𝘺 𝘰𝘧 𝘍𝘰𝘳𝘦𝘯𝘴𝘪𝘤 𝘚𝘤𝘪𝘦𝘯𝘤𝘦 𝘧𝘳𝘰𝘮 𝘚𝘩𝘦𝘳𝘭𝘰𝘤𝘬 𝘏𝘰𝘭𝘮𝘦𝘴 𝘵𝘰 𝘋𝘕𝘈, students in Ms. Kelli Floyd's 10th grade Honors ELA class prepared for a CSI Case Study presented to them in front of Judge Andy Bethea at the Dillon County Judicial Complex. The Sheriff's Department allowed them to perform a secondary fingerprint analysis, where they also met with Dillon County Coroner Donnie Grimsley to discuss the role of a coroner.
text:
LAKE VIEW HIGH SCHOOL:

After reading 𝘉𝘭𝘰𝘰𝘥, 𝘉𝘶𝘭𝘭𝘦𝘵𝘴, 𝘢𝘯𝘥 𝘉𝘰𝘯𝘦𝘴: 𝘛𝘩𝘦 𝘚𝘵𝘰𝘳𝘺 𝘰𝘧 𝘍𝘰𝘳𝘦𝘯𝘴𝘪𝘤 𝘚𝘤𝘪𝘦𝘯𝘤𝘦 𝘧𝘳𝘰𝘮 𝘚𝘩𝘦𝘳𝘭𝘰𝘤𝘬 𝘏𝘰𝘭𝘮𝘦𝘴 𝘵𝘰 𝘋𝘕𝘈, students in Ms. Kelli Floyd's 10th grade Honors ELA class prepared for a CSI Case Study presented to them in front of Judge Andy Bethea at the Dillon County Judicial Complex. The Sheriff's Department allowed them to perform a secondary fingerprint analysis, where they also met with Dillon County Coroner Donnie Grimsley to discuss the role of a coroner.

LAKE VIEW HIGH SCHOOL:

Mr. Daniels' Honors Physics and his two Physical Science classes are on the Electricity and Circuits Unit. The students are exploring how a simple series circuit and an electric motor will power a fan to move their wooden box cars. They also have to figure out the best design that will allow their car to move the fastest and win the race against their other classmates. This project will not only use the skills they just learned about circuits and motors, but also test their scientific investigation skills.

DILLON MIDDLE SCHOOL:

On Saturday, February 22, 2020, students of the Dillon Middle School Band Program had the opportunity to participate in the Region 5 Honor Band Clinic which was held at Myrtle Beach High School in Myrtle Beach, SC.

In order for students to be selected for this honor band, students had to play seven scales, define musical terms, sight-read and play a solo. We were glad to have the following students to represent the DMS Band Program:

Left to Right
1. Zaniyah McKellar - Contra Eb Clarinet
2. Madison Nelson - Trombone
3. Azzure' Mosley - Clarinet
4. Shaniyah Roberts - Clarinet
5. Da'Naisha Phillips - Clarinet
6. Ian Myers - Bassoon
7. L'Nauhre' Bethea - Trumpet
8. Janaya Pernell - Contra Bb Bass Clarinet

LAKE VIEW HIGH SCHOOL:

After reading the chapter about fingerprint evidence in 𝘉𝘭𝘰𝘰𝘥, 𝘉𝘶𝘭𝘭𝘦𝘵𝘴, & 𝘉𝘰𝘯𝘦𝘴, students conducted a fingerprint analysis lab and followed up with a lab report and fingerprint search. We even fingerprinted Mr. Arnette, LVHS Principal!

Next week they’ll read a "Whodunnit?" and prepare to argue the case in front of a local judge at the nearby Judicial Complex, as well as perform a secondary fingerprint analysis with the Sheriff’s Department. They’ll also meet the county coroner! We can’t wait!

LAKE VIEW HIGH SCHOOL:

Mrs. Lauren Ray's 7th grade ELA classes just completed the novel, 𝘛𝘩𝘦 𝘖𝘶𝘵𝘴𝘪𝘥𝘦𝘳𝘴. Her 4th block students were then asked to create a 3D diorama on a scene from the book. The students chose a scene to depict, gathered materials they needed, created their diorama inside of a shoe box, and wrote up a clear explanation of the scene. Students were very creative and did a fantastic job on their dioramas!

LAKE VIEW HIGH SCHOOL:

Students in Mrs. Sharon Williams’ seventh grade science class are shown creating edible cells. Ms. Erika Jones, Dillon and Marlboro 4-H and Youth Development Agent, brought in a variety of candies to use as the different organelles and cookies were used as the animal cell. The objective was for the students to create an animal cell, explain the organelles used, and describe the purpose of the organelle. The students were then able to eat and enjoy their “cell.”

DILLON HIGH SCHOOL:

GT Honors Chorus Students Essay Winners Essays were judged and prizes awarded on Thursday, January 30, 2020. The awards were presented by Jayne Lee, DSD4 Director of Assessment and Instructional Support. Two first place winners received $50.00 prizes: Emeline Niyibitanga and Kannaji Peppers. Four second place winners were awarded $25.00 prizes: Saheed Bethea, Sinaayah Mathis, Dukunde Marie-Paredes and Ja’Naysia Rowell. One third place winner received a $15.00 prize: Brallam Marroquin. The field trip and essay contest was supported by funds from the Hootie & the Blowfish Grant which is a three year $30,000 grant administered by Central Carolina Community Foundation.

LAKE VIEW HIGH SCHOOL:

Mrs. Gasque's 6th Grade science classes investigated simple machines and compound machines. The students discovered the apple peeler is a compound machine that involves three simple machines - the screw, the wedge and the wheel & axle. This particular apple peeler also had an additional wedge which sliced the apple. The students gained an understanding on how simple machines and compound machines make work easier. They also enjoyed the fruits of their labor by eating a peeled and sliced apple!

Reminder: School starts at 8:00 A.M. Instruction begins promptly at 8:00 A.M. Personnel will be stationed outside of our front gate. If arriving after 8:00 A.M., parents will be directed to park and bring their child to the front office. All students who are tardy must be signed in by a parent to receive a tardy slip to enter class.

School dismisses at 2:30 for car riders. Parents are asked to come in to the school and sign their student out if they have not been picked up by 2:50. Thank you!
